Hypothesis Testing

In null hypothesis significant testing, we are testing the validity of a claim about a population against a counter claim using sample data.

Null Hypothesis, H0: A hypothesis claiming no difference between sample and population

Alternative Hypothesis, HA: A hypothesis contradicting H0, which is usually what we're trying to prove.

Test Statistic, T: A statistic used to test our hypothesis.

Significance Level, α: Probability threshold of rejection of H0. This is the probability of getting a type I error.

p-value: The probability of observing a statistic as extreme or more extreme than the one observed under the assumption that H0 is true.

Power of the Test: Probability of rejecting H0 when HA is true.

α=p(rejectH0|H0)=p(Type I Error)=p(False Positive)
1−α=p(do not rejectH0|HA)=p(True Negative)
β=p(do not rejectH0|HA)=p(Type II Error)=p(False Negative)
1−β=p(rejectH0|HA)=p(True Positive)=Power of the Test

z-Test

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn
  • xi∼N(μ,σ2)
  • μ is unknown, σ2 is known

Null Hypothesis

H0:μ=μ0

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μ>μ0,μ<μ0,orμ≠μ0

Test Statistic

z=x¯−μ0σ/n

Null Distribution

Standard Normal Distribution:Z∼N(0,1)

p-Value

z-Test: Two Samples

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn and y1,y2,...,ym
  • xi∼N(μx,σx2), yi∼N(μy,σy2)
  • μx,μy are unknown, σx2,σy2 are known

Null Hypothesis

H0:μx−μy=μ0

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μx−μy>μ0,μx−μy<μ0,orμx−μy≠μ0

Test Statistic

z=x¯−y¯−μ0σp

where σp2 is the pooled population variance:

σp2=σx2n+σy2m

Null Distribution

Standard Normal Distribution:Z∼N(0,1)

p-Value

t-Test

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn
  • xi∼N(μ,σ2)
  • μ,σ2 are unknown

Null Hypothesis

H0:μ=μ0

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μ>μ0,μ<μ0,orμ≠μ0

Test Statistic

t=x¯−μ0s/n

Null Distribution

t-Distribution:T∼t(n−1)

p-Value

t-Test: Two Samples with Equal Variances

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn and y1,y2,...,ym
  • xi∼N(μx,σ2), yi∼N(μy,σ2)
  • μx,μy,σ2 are unknown

Null Hypothesis

H0:μx−μy=μ0

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μx−μy>μ0,μx−μy<μ0,orμx−μy≠μ0

Test Statistic

t=x¯−y¯−μ0sp

where sp2 is the pooled sample variance:

sp2=(n−1)sx2+(m−1)sy2n+m−2×(1n+1m)

Null Distribution

t-Distribution:T∼t(n+m−2)

p-Value

t-Test: Two Samples with Unequal Variances

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn and y1,y2,...,ym
  • xi∼N(μx,σx2), yi∼N(μy,σy2)
  • μx,μy,σx2,σy2 are unknown

Null Hypothesis

H0:μx−μy=μ0

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μx−μy>μ0,μx−μy<μ0,orμx−μy≠μ0

Test Statistic

t=x¯−y¯−μ0sp

where sp2 is the pooled sample variance:

sp2=sx2n+sy2m

Null Distribution

t-Distribution (approximation):T∼t(df)

where df is the degrees of freedom, defined by,

df=⌊(sx2/n+sy2/m)2(sx2/n)2/(n−1)+(sy2/m)2/(m−1)⌉

where ⌊a⌉ is the nearest integer of a.

F-Test for Equal Means (One Way ANOVA)

Assumptions

  • Samples: n sets of m samples, xij;i=1,2,...,n;j=1,2,...,m
  • xij∼N(μi,σ2)
  • μi,σ2 are unknown

Null Hypothesis

H0:μ1=μ2=...=μn

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:μi≠μjfor somei,j

Test Statistic

v=MSbMSw

where,

Mean Squared Sum Within Sets,MSw=SSwn(m−1)Mean Squared Sum Between Sets,MSb=SSbn−1Squared Sum Within Sets,SSw=∑i=1n∑j=1m(xij−xi¯)2=∑i=1n(m−1)si2Squared Sum Between Sets,SSb=∑i=1nm(xi¯−x¯)2

Null Distribution

F-Distribution:V∼F(n−1,n(m−1))

F-Test for Equal Variances

Assumptions

  • Samples: x1,x2,...,xn and y1,y2,...,ym
  • xi∼N(μx,σx2), yi∼N(μy,σy2)
  • μx,μy,σx2,σy2 are unknown

Null Hypothesis

H0:σx=σy

Alternative Hypothesis

HA:σx>σy,σx<σyorσx≠σy

Test Statistic

v=sx2sy2

Null Distribution

F-Distribution:V∼F(n−1,m−1)

p-Value
